data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` ŌĆö now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your expression-tree construction **won't compile** anymore. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The new overload accepts a regular lambda, so conditional setters are now trivial ŌĆö no manual `Expression.Call`/`Expression.Lambda` needed.

---

### 2. Complex type columns ŌĆö names are now **uniquified** and nested paths are **fully qualified**

Two sub-changes:

- **Shared names get a numeric suffix.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously mapped to the same `Street` column (silent data corruption risk). EF 10 auto-uniquifies them (`Street`, `Street1`).
- **Nested complex types use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` now maps to column `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of `BillingAddress_City`.

Both changes generate migrations that **rename existing columns**, which will break your database unless you pin the old names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street")); // keep shared column if intentional
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old column name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");  // old convention
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` ŌĆö new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Your class won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ŌåÉ new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants are redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
